\u00b2)\n! Density (/km\u00b2)\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Arunachal Pradesh ||  1,383,727 || 713,912 || 669,815 || 938 || 65.38 || 870,087\n| 227,881 || 83,743 || 17\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Assam || 31,205,576 || 15,939,443 || 15,266,133 || 958 || 72.19 || 23,216,288\n| 3,439,240 || 78,438 || 397\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Manipur || 2,570,390 || 1,290,171 || 1,280,219 || 992 || 79.21 || 1,590,820 || 575,968\n| 22,327 || 122\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Meghalaya || 2,966,889 || 1,491,832 || 1,475,057 || 989 || 74.43 || 1,864,711 || 454,111\n| 22,429 || 132\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Mizoram || 1,097,206 || 555,339 || 541,867 || 976 || 91.33 || 447,567 || 441,006\n| 21,081 || 52\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Nagaland || 1,978,502 || 1,024,649 || 953,853 || 931 || 79.55 || 1,647,249 || 342,787\n| 16,579 || 119\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Sikkim || 610,577 || 323,070 || 287,507 || 890 || 81.42 || 480,981 || 59,870 || 7,096\n| 86\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Tripura || 3,673,917 || 1,874,376 || 1,799,541 || 960 || 87.22 || 2,653,453 || 545,750\n| 10,486 || 350\n|}\n\n===Largest cities by population===\n{{main|List of cities in India by population|List of cities in Assam by population}}\nAccording to [[2011 Census of India]], the largest cities in Northeast India are \n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:0.9em;background:#ffffff;text-align:center;min-width:70%;\"\n! Rank !! City !! Type !!State !!Population !!Rank !! City !! Type !!State !!Population\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|1 || [[Guwahati]] ||align=\"center\"|UA||Assam || align=\"right\" | 968,549||style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|9 || [[Jorhat]]  ||UA ||Assam|| align=\"right\" | 153,889\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|2 || [[Agartala]]  ||style=\"background:#fEE0F2;\"|City||Tripura || align=\"right\" | 522,613|| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|10 || [[Nagaon]]  ||UA ||Assam|| align=\"right\" | 147,496\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|3 || [[Imphal]]  ||align=\"center\"|UA ||Manipur|| align=\"right\" |  414,288||style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|11 || [[Tinsukia]]  ||UA ||Assam|| align=\"right\" | 126,389\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|4 || [[Dimapur]]   ||style=\"background:#fEE0F2;\"|City||Nagaland|| align=\"right\" | 379,769|| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|12 || [[Dhubri]]  ||UA ||Assam|| align=\"right\" | 109,234\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|5 || [[Shillong]]  ||UA ||Meghalaya|| align=\"right\" | 354,325|| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|13 || [[Tezpur]]  ||UA ||Assam|| align=\"right\" | 102,505\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|6 || [[Aizawl]]   ||style=\"background:#fEE0F2;\"|City ||Mizoram|| align=\"right\" |  291,822|| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|14 || [[Kohima]]  ||UA ||Nagaland|| align=\"right\" | 100,000\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|7 || [[Silchar]]   ||UA ||Assam|| align=\"right\" | 229,136|| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|15 || [[Gangtok]]  ||style=\"background:#fEE0F2;\"|City ||Sikkim || align=\"right\" | 98,658\n|- \n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|8 || [[Dibrugarh]]  ||UA  ||Assam|| align=\"right\" | 154,296|| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|16 || [[Itanagar]]  ||style=\"background:#fEE0F2;\"|City ||Arunachal Pradesh|| align=\"right\" | 95,650\n|-\n| colspan=\"10\" align=\"left\"|\n''UA'': Urban Agglomeration<ref>http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_3_PR_UA_Citiees_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf</ref>\n|- \n|}\n\n===Languages===\nNortheast India constitutes a single linguistic region within the Indian national context, with about 220 languages in multiple language families ([[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]], [[Sino-Tibetan languages|Sino-Tibetan]], [[Kra\u2013Dai languages|Kra\u2013Dai]], [[Austroasiatic languages|Austroasiatic]], as well as some creole languages) that share a number of features that set them apart from most other areas of the Indian subcontinent (such as alveolar consonants rather than the more typical dental/retroflex distinction).<ref name=\"moral97_42\">{{harv|Moral|1997|p=42}}</ref><ref name=\"IITG-languages_of_ne\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.iitg.ernet.in/rcilts/phaseI/heirarchy.htm |title=IITG - Hierarchy of North Eastern Languages}}</ref> [[Assamese language|Assamese]], an [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan language]] spoken mostly in the [[Brahmaputra Valley]], developed as a ''lingua franca'' for many speech communities.  Assamese-based pidgin/creoles have developed in Nagaland ([[Nagamese]]) and Arunachal ([[Nefamese]]),<ref>{{harv|Moral|1997|pp=43\u201344}}</ref> though their use has been on a decline in recent times.  The Austro-Asiatic family is represented by the [[Khasi language|Khasi]], [[Jaintia language|Jaintia]] and [[War language|War]] languages of Meghalaya. A small number of Tai\u2013Kadai languages (Ahom, Tai Phake, Khamti, etc.) are also spoken. Sino-Tibetan is represented by a number of languages that differ significantly from each other,<ref name=BlenchPost13>Blench, R. & Post, M. W. (2013). [https://www.academia.edu/627686/Rethinking_Sino-Tibetan_phylogeny_from_the_perspective_of_North_East_Indian_languages Rethinking Sino-Tibetan phylogeny from the perspective of Northeast Indian languages]</ref> some of which are: [[Bodo language|Bodo]], Rabha, Karbi, Mising, Tiwa, [[Deori language|Deori]], Biate etc. (Assam); Garo, Hajong, Biate (Meghalaya) Ao, Angami, Sema, Lotha, Konyak etc.(Nagaland); Mizo, [[Hmar language|Hmar]], [[Chakma language|Chakma]] etc. (Mizoram); Hrusso, Tanee, Nisi, Adi, Abor, Nocte, Apatani, Misimi etc. (Arunachal). [[Meitei language|Meitei]] is the official language in Manipur, the dominant language of the Imphal Valley; while \"Naga\" languages such as [[Poula language|Poumai]], [[Sopvoma language|Mao]], Maram, Rongmei (Kabui) and Tangkul, and Kuki-Chin languages such as Thadou-Kuki, Mizo, [[Hmar language|Hmar]], Simte and Paite predominate in individual hill areas of the state.<ref name=PostBurling17>Post, M. W. and R. Burling (2017). [https://www.academia.edu/17070971/The_Tibeto-Burman_languages_of_Northeast_India The Tibeto-Burman languages of Northeast India]</ref>\n\nAmong other Indo-Aryan languages, [[Bengali language|Bengali]] is spoken in South Assam in the Barak Valley. Besides the Sino-Tibetan [[Kokborok|Tripuri language]], [[Bengali language|Bengali]] is a majority language in Tripura. [[Nepali language|Nepali]], an Indo-Aryan language, is dominant in [[Sikkim]], besides the Sino-Tibetan languages [[Limbu language|Limbu]], [[Bhutia language|Bhutia]] and [[Lepcha language|Lepcha]]. Bengali was the official language of [[Colonial Assam]] for about forty years from the 1830s.\n\n====Official languages====\n{{See also|Languages with official status in India}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:0.9em;min-width:70%;background:#ffffff;\"\n|-\n! State\n! Official Languages<ref name=\"NER official languages\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.mcrg.ac.in/Core/Northeast_Report.pdf |title=Report On North East India}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Arunachal Pradesh || [[Hindi language|Hindi]], [[English language|English]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Assam || [[Assamese language|Assamese]], [[Bengali language|Bengali]] (in the [[Barak Valley]]), [[Bodo language|Bodo]] (in [[Bodoland]])\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Manipur || [[Meitei language|Meiteilon]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Meghalaya || [[Khasi language|Khasi]], [[Garo language|Garo]], [[English language|English]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Mizoram || [[Mizo language|Mizo]], [[English language|English]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Nagaland || [[English language|English]]<ref name=\"Nagaland State Profile\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nagaland.gov.in/portal/portal/StatePortal/AboutNagaland/StateProfile |title=Nagaland State Profile}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Sikkim || [[Nepali language|Nepali]], [[English language|English]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Tripura || [[Bengali language|Bengali]], [[Kokborok]], [[English language|English]]<ref>https://tripura.gov.in/know-tripura</ref>\n|}\n\n====Etymology of state names====\n{{See also|Nomenclature of States in North East India|List of Indian state and union territory name etymologies}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:0.9em;min-width:70%;background:#ffffff;\"\n|-\n! Name of state\n! Origin\n! Literal meaning\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Arunachal Pradesh || [[Sanskrit]] || ''Land of the rising sun''\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|[[Etymology of Assam|Assam]] ||  Native word || Name derived from the ''[[Ahom people]](?)''<ref>\"Ahoms also gave Assam and its language their name ('\n|'Ahom'' and the modern ''\u0252\u03c7\u0252m'' 'Assam' come from an attested earlier form ''asam'', ''acam'', probably from a Burmese corruption of the word ''Shan/Shyam'', cf. ''Siam'': Kakati 1962; 1-4).\" {{harv|Masica|1993|p=50}}</ref>, and also from the Sanskrit word ''asama'', meaning \"uneven\"(?)<ref>\"According to some, the word is derived from ''Asama''meaning \"uneven\", as distinguished from Samatata, or the level plains of East Bengal.\" {{harv|Gait|1906|p=241}}</ref> \n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|[[wiktionary:Manipur|Manipur]] || [[Sanskrit]] || ''Land abundant with jewels'', adopted in the 18th century\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Meghalaya || [[Sanskrit]] || ''Abode of the clouds'', coined by [[Shiba P. Chatterjee]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Mizoram || [[Mizo language]] ||  ''Land of the Hilly people''; ''Ram'' - means land \n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Nagaland || [[English language|English]] || ''Land of the Naga people''\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Sikkim || [[Limbu language|Limbu Language]] || ''New House'' \u2013 Derived from the word ''\"Sukhim\"'', \"Su\" meaning new and \"Khim\" meaning house\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|[[Tripura#Etymology|Tripura]] || [[Kokborok]] || [[Sanskrit]] version of native names: Tipra, Tuipura, [[Twipra Kingdom|Twipra]] etc. It literally means ''Land near the Water'' \u2013 Derived from the word ''\"TWIPRA\"'', \"Twi\" meaning water and \"Bupra\" meaning near. As [[Tripura]] is slightly near the [[Bay of Bengal]]\n|}\n\n====Endangered languages====\n{{Main|List of endangered languages in India}}\nGiven the diverse population in the region with only a few widely spoken ones recognised as the [[official language]]s by both the [[State government|state]] and [[Central government|central]] governments, a large number of languages from the North Eastern Region of [[India]] have become vulnerable. Without proper teaching and preservation efforts, the already underdeveloped [[literature]] of the endangered languages are on the verge of extinction. Additionally, the younger generation are rapidly adopting the widely spoken languages to secure employment and livelihood.<ref name=\"Endangered languages of North-east India\">{{Cite web |url=https://smritikumarsinha.wordpress.com/northeast-a-war-and-peace-painting/ |title=Endangered languages of North-east India}}</ref>\n\n===Religions===\n\n{{Pie chart |thumb = right\n|caption = Religion in Northeast India (2011)\n|label1 = [[Hinduism]]|color1 = Orange\n|value1 = 58.06\n|label2 = [[Islam]]|color2 = Green \n|value2 = 23\n|label3 = [[Christianity]]|color3 = DodgerBlue\n|value3 = 16.89\n|label4 = [[Buddhism]]|color4 = Lavender\n|value4 = 1.37\n|label5 = [[Jainism]]|color5 = Tomato\n|value5 = 0.07\n|label6 = [[Sikhism]]|color6 = MediumTurquoise\n|value6 = 0.07\n|label7 = Other religions|color7 = DeepPink\n|value7 = 1.65\n|label8 = Not Stated|color8 = Black\n|value8 = 0.19\n}}\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size:0.9em;text-align:right;background:#ffffff;min-width:70%;\"\n|+ style=\"text-align:left;\"|Religious population in North Eastern Region, according to [[2011 Census of India]]<ref name=\"2011 Census of India - Population By Religious Community\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/C-01.html|title=Population By Religious Community}}</ref>\n! State !! Hinduism !! Islam !! Christianity !! Buddhism !! Jainism !! Sikhism !! Other Religions !! Religion Not Stated\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Arunachal Pradesh || 401,876 || 27,045 || 418,732 || 162,815 || 771 || 3,287 || 362,553 || 6,648\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Assam || 19,180,759 || 10,679,345 || 1,165,867 || 54,993 || 25,949 || 20,672 || 27,118 || 50,873\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Manipur || 1,181,876 || 239,836 || 1,179,043 || 7,084 || 1,692 || 1,527 || 233,767 || 10,969\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Meghalaya || 342,078 || 130,399 || 2,213,027 || 9,864 || 627 || 3,045 || 258,271 || 9,578\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Mizoram || 30,136 || 14,832 || 956,331 || 93,411 || 376 || 286 || 808 || 1,026\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Nagaland || 173,054 || 48,963 || 1,739,651 || 6,759 || 2,655 || 1,890 || 3,214 || 2,316\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Sikkim || 352,662 || 9,867 || 60,522 || 167,216 || 314 || 1,868 || 16,300 || 1,828\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Tripura || 3,063,903 || 316,042 || 159,882 || 125,385 || 860 || 1,070 || 1,514 || 5,261\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|'''Total''' || '''24,726,344''' || '''11,466,329''' || '''7,893,055''' || '''627,527''' || '''33,244''' || '''33,645''' || '''903,545''' || '''88,499'''\n|-\n|}\n\n===Ethnic groups===\nNortheast India has over 220 ethnic groups and an equal number of dialects in which [[Bodo people|Bodo]] form the largest indigenous ethnic group.<ref name=\"Tribal groups in Assam and Northeast India\">{{Cite web |url=http://factsanddetails.com/india/Minorities_Castes_and_Regions_in_India/sub7_4f/entry-4210.html |title=Tribal groups in Assam and Northeast India}}</ref> The hills states in the region like [[Arunachal Pradesh]], [[Meghalaya]], [[Mizoram]], and [[Nagaland]] are predominantly inhabited by tribal people with a degree of diversity even within the tribal groups. The region's population results from ancient and continuous flows of migrations from Tibet, Indo-Gangetic India, the Himalayas, present Bangladesh, and Myanmar.<ref>van Driem, G. (2012)</ref>\n\n====Major communities====\n{{colbegin|colwidth=10em}}\n{{plainlist|\n* [[Adivasi]]\n* [[Ahom people|Ahom]]\n* [[Angami Naga|Angami]]\n* [[Ao Naga|Ao]]\n* [[An\u0101l Naga]]\n* [[Apatani people|Apatani]]\n* [[Assamese people|Assamese]]\n* [[Bahun]]\n* [[Bengali people|Bengali]] \n* [[Bhutia]]\n* [[Bisnupriya Manipuri people|Bishnupriya]]\n* [[Biate people|Biate]]\n* [[Bodo people|Bodo]]\n* [[Bru people|Bru]]\n* [[Chakhesang]]\n* [[Chakma people|Chakma]]\n* [[Chhetri]]\n* [[Chutiya]]\n* [[Chorei language|Chorei]]\n* [[Deori people|Deori]]\n* [[Dimasa people|Dimasa]]\n* [[Garo people|Garo]]\n* [[Gurung people|Gurung]]\n* [[Hajong people|Hajong]]\n* [[Hmar people|Hmar]]\n* [[Jamatia]]\n* [[Karbi people|Karbi]]\n* [[Kami]]\n* [[Khasi people|Khasi]]\n* [[Khampti]]\n* [[Koch Rajbongshi people|Koch]]\n* [[Kom people (India)|Kom]]\n* [[Konyak people|Konyak]]\n* [[Kuki people|Kuki]]\n* [[Lepcha people|Lepcha]]\n* [[Limbu]]\n* [[Lotha Naga|Lotha]]\n* [[Magar (Maharashtra)|Magar]]\n* [[Mao Naga|Mao]]\n* [[Maram Naga|Maram]]\n* [[Meitei people|Meitei]]\n* [[Mishing People|Mishing]]\n* [[Mizo people|Mizo]]\n* [[Mara people|Mara]]\n* [[Monsang Naga|Monsang]]\n* [[Mishmi people|Mishmi]]\n* [[Naga people|Naga]]\n* [[People of Nepal|Nepali]]\n* [[Noatia]] \n* [[Paite people|Paite]]\n* [[Pnar people|Pnar]]\n* [[Poumai Naga|Poumai]]\n* [[Purvottar maithili]]\n* [[Rai (ethnic group)|Rai]]\n* [[Rabha]]\n* [[Ranglong language|Ranglong]] (''Langrong'')\n* [[Reang]]\n* [[Rongmei Naga|Rongmei]]\n* [[Sangtam Naga|Sangtam]]\n* [[Sumi Naga|Sumi]]\n* [[Singpho people|Singpho]]\n*[[Sonowal Kachari]]\n* [[Sylheti language|Sylheti]]\n* [[Tamang people|Tamang]]\n* [[Tangkhul Naga|Tangkhul]]\n* [[Tiwa (Lalung)|Tiwa]]\n* [[Thengal Kachari]]\n* [[Tripuri people|Tripuri]]\n* [[Yimchunger]]\n* [[Zomi people]] (Paite, Vaiphei, Zou, Teddim, Simte, Gangte)\n}}\n{{colend}}\n<br />\n<gallery>\nFile:British India map of Northeast India and Myanmar, Bengal Assam Meghalaya Arunachal Pradesh Nagaland Manipur Mizoram Tripura regions 1891.jpg|<center>British India map of Northeast India by ethnicity, 1891</center>\nFile:\u0422\u0430\u043d\u0446\u043e\u0440 \u043f\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438 \u043d\u0430\u0433\u0430.JPG|<center>A [[Naga people|Naga]] warrior in 1960</center>\nFile:Bishnupriya Manipuri Bride.jpg|<center>[[Bisnupriya Manipuri Society|Bishnupuriya]] bride</center>\nFile:SHAD SUK MYNSIEM.jpg|<center>Shad suk Mynsiem, a [[Khasi people|Khasi]] festival</center>\nFile:Traditional Hajong Clothing, Pathin and Argon.jpg|<center>Traditional [[Hajong people|Hajong]] Clothing</center>\nFile:Aka Tribe.jpg|<center>Aka tribe, [[Arunachal Pradesh]]</center>\nFile:Mizo school girls.jpg|<center>[[Mizo people|Mizo]] school girls</center>\nFile:Fruit sellers in Senapati, Manipur, India..JPG|<center>Women selling fruits in [[Senapati district|Senapati]], [[Manipur]]</center>\nFile:Sister of the King of Sikkim in traditional royal dress, 30214u.tif|<center>Princess of [[Sikkim]] in traditional royal dress</center>\nFile:Tripuri Childrens.jpg|<center>[[Tripuri people|Tipra]] children in traditional attire grouping up for song presentation</center>\nFile:Assamese Bihu.jpg|[[Assamese people|Asamiya]] youth in Bihu attire. \n</gallery>\n[[File:Mizo girls in Mizo traditional dress.jpg|thumb|Mizo girls in Mizo traditional dress]]\n\n==Culture==\n===Cuisines===\n{{Main|Indian cuisine}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:0.9em;min-width:70%;background:#ffffff;\"\n! State\n! Staple diet\n! Popular dishes\n! Related article\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Arunachal Pradesh||Rice, fish, meat, [[leaf vegetables]]||[[Thukpa]], [[Momo (food)|momo]], ''apong'' ([[rice beer]])||[[Cuisine of Arunachal Pradesh]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Assam||Rice, fish, meat, [[leaf vegetable]]||[[Assam tea]], [[Pitha]], ''khar'', ''tenga'', ''pura'', tamul ([[betel nut]]) \u2013 [[paan]], [[rice beer]]  ||[[Assamese cuisine]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Manipur||Rice, fish, local vegetables||''[[Eromba]]'', ''[[u-morok]]'', ''[[singju]]'', ''ngari'' (fermented fish), ''kangshoi''||[[Cuisine of Manipur]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Meghalaya||Rice, spiced meat, fish||''Jadoh'', ''ki kpu'', ''minil'', ''nakham'' (dried fish), [[Momo (food)|momo]], [[bamboo shoot]]||[[Cuisine of Meghalaya]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Mizoram||Rice, fish, meat||''Bai'', ''bekang'' (fermented soya beans), ''sa-um'' (fermented pork), ''sawhchiar''||\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Nagaland||Rice, meat, stewed or steamed vegetables||fermented bamboo shoot, smoked pork and beef, ''axone'', ''[[bhut jolokia]]''||[[Naga cuisine]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Sikkim||Rice, meat, dairy products||[[Thukpa]], [[Momo (food)|momo]], [[sha Phaley]], [[gundruk]], [[Sinki (food)|sinki]], [[sel roti]]||[[Sikkimese cuisine]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Tripura||Rice, fish, meat||Fish stew, [[bamboo shoot]], fermented fish|| [[Tripuri cuisine]]\n|}\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Naga thali.JPG|<center>[[Naga cuisine|Nagamese meal]]</center>\nFile:Bhangui.PNG|<center>''Bhangui'' - ethnic food of [[Tripura]]</center>\nFile:Paknam.JPG|<center>''Paknam'' ([[Cuisine of Manipur|Manipur]])</center>\nFile:Smoked freshwater fish.JPG|<center>Smoked freshwater fish ([[Cuisine of Manipur|Manipur]])</center>\nFile:A bowl of Thukpa.jpg|<center>[[Thukpa]] - a popular Northeast India cuisine</center>\nFile:Food in Lachung, North Sikkim.JPG|<center>[[North Sikkim district|North Sikkim]] meal</center>\nFile:Assamese dish.JPG|<center>[[Assamese cuisine|Assamese]] ''thali''</center>\nFile:Red Rice With Pork pieces.jpg|<center>Red rice with pork ([[Arunachal Pradesh]])</center>\n</gallery>\n\n===Arts===\n[[Sattriya]] (from [[Assam]]) and [[Manipuri dance]] (from [[Manipur]]) have been listed as [[Indian classical dance|classical dances of India]]. Besides these, all tribes in Northeast India have their own folk dances associated with their religion and festivals. The tribal heritage in the region is rich with the practice of hunting, land cultivation and indigenous crafts. The rich culture is vibrant and visible with the traditional attires of each community.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nAll states in Northeast India share the handicrafts of [[bamboo]] and [[cane (grass)|cane]], [[wood carving]], making traditional weapons and musical instruments, pottery and handloom weaving. Traditional tribal attires are made of thick fabrics primarily with cotton.<ref name=\"Northeast India craft forms\" /> [[Assam silk]] is a famous industry in the region.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:0.9em;min-width:70%;text-align:left;background:#ffffff;\"\n! State\n! Traditional [[Performing Arts]]\n! Traditional [[Visual Arts]]\n! Traditional [[Crafts]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Arunachal Pradesh||Wancho dances, Idu Mishmi dance, Digaru Mishmi Buiya dance, Khampti dance, Ponung dance, Sadinuktso<ref name=\"Culture of Arunachal Pradesh\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.webindia123.com/arunachal/arts/dance.htm |title=Arunachal Pradesh |authorlink=webindia123}}</ref>|| ||[[Arundo|Cane]] and [[bamboo]], cotton and wool weaving, wood carving, blacksmithy (hand tools, weapons, ornaments, dishes, sacred bells and smoking pipes)<ref name=\"Culture of Arunachal Pradesh\" /><ref name=\"Arts and crafts of North-east India\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ignca.nic.in/craft001.htm |title=Arts and crafts of North-east India |authorlink=IGNCA}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Assam||[[Sattriya]], ''[[Bagurumba]]'', [[Bihu dance]], [[Bhaona]] (For more see [[Music of Assam]])||[[Hastividyarnava]] (For more see [[Fine Arts of Assam]])||[[Arundo|Cane]] and [[bamboo]], [[Kamrupi crafts|bell metal and brass]], [[Assam silk|silk]], toy and mask making, [[pottery]] and [[terracotta]], jewellery, musical instruments making, boat making, paints\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Manipur||[[Manipuri dance]] (Ras Lila), ''Kartal Cholom'', ''Manjira Cholom'', ''Khubak Eshei'', ''Pung Cholom'', ''Lai-Haraoba''|| ||[[Cotton]] textile, [[bamboo]] crafts (hats, baskets), [[pottery]]<ref name=\"Arts and crafts of North-east India\" /><ref name=\"Northeast India craft forms\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nelive.in/north-east/art-culture/top-5-craft-forms-land-north-east |title=Northeast India craft forms \u2013 nelive.in}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Meghalaya||''Nongkrem'', ''Shad suk'', ''Behdienkhlam'', ''Wangala'', ''Lahoo'' dance<ref name=\"Popular dances of Meghalaya\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.north-east-india.com/meghalaya/music-dance-meghalaya.html |title=Popular dances of Meghalaya}}</ref><ref name=\"Arts and crafts of North-east India\" /> (For more see [[Music of Meghalaya]])|| ||Making hand tools and weapons, musical instruments (drums), [[Arundo|cane]] and [[bamboo]] work, weaving traditional attires, jewellery making (gold, coral, glass), wall engravings, wood carving<ref name=\"Arts and crafts of North-east India\" /><ref name=\"Meghalaya handicrafts\">{{Cite web |url=http://camelcraft.com/meghalaya-handicrafts.html |title=Meghalaya handicrafts}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Mizoram||''Cheraw'', ''Khuallam'', ''Chheih-Lam'', ''Chai'', ''Rallu-Lam'', ''Solakia'', ''Sarlamkai'', ''Par-lam'', ''Sakei Lu Lam''<ref name=\"Mizoram dances\">{{Cite web |url=http://ignca.nic.in/craft205.htm#Dances |title=Dances in Mizoram}}</ref> (For more see [[Music of Mizoram]])|| ||Traditional hand tools, weapons and textile work, [[bamboo]] and [[Arundo|cane]] handicrafts<ref name=\"Mizoram handicrafts\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.camelcraft.com/mizoram-handicrafts.html |title=Mizoram handicrafts}}</ref><ref name=\"Arts and crafts of North-east India\" />\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Nagaland||[[Zeliangrong|Zeliang]] dance, war dance, ''Nruirolians'' (cock dance) (For more see [[Music of Nagaland]])|| ||[[Arundo|Cane]] and [[bamboo]] crafts, traditional hand tools, weapons and textile work, [[wood carving]], [[pottery]], ornaments for traditional attire, musical instruments ([[drum]] and [[trumpet]])<ref name=\"Arts and crafts of North-east India\" />\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Sikkim||''Chu Faat'' dance, ''Lu Khangthamo'', ''Gha To Kito'', ''Rechungma'', ''Maruni'', ''[[Tamang Selo]]'', ''Singhi Chaam'', Yak Chaam, [[Khukuri]] dance, Rumtek Chaam (mask dance)<ref name=\"Sikkim dances\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bharatonline.com/sikkim/culture/folk-dance.html |title=Sikkim dances}}</ref><ref name=\"Culture of Sikkim\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.sikkimonline.in/about/Profile/Culture/index.html |title=Culture of Sikkim \u2013 sikkimonline.in}}</ref><ref name=\"Folk dances of Sikkim\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nelive.in/sikkim/art-culture/folk-dances-sikkim |title=Folk dances of Sikkim}}</ref> (See also [[Music of Sikkim]])||''[[Thangka]]'' (showcasing [[Buddhism|Buddhist teachings]] on cotton canvas using vegetable dyes)<ref name=\"Culture of Sikkim\" /> ||[[Handmade paper]], carpet making, woollen textile, [[wood carving]]<ref name=\"Culture of Sikkim\" />\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Tripura||[[Goria dance]], [[Jhum dance]], [[Lebang dance]], [[Mamita dance]], [[Mosak sulmani dance]], [[Hojagiri dance]], [[Bizhu dance]], [[Wangala]], [[Hai-hak dance]], [[Sangrai dance]], [[Owa dance]]|| ||[[Arundo|Cane]] and [[bamboo]], weaving and handloom, ''sitalpati'' (mat making), [[wood carving]],<ref name=\"Arts and crafts of North-east India\" /> [[String instrument|string]] and [[Wind instrument|wind musical instruments]]\n|}\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Satriya dance at Rabindra Bhawan.JPG|<center>[[Sattriya|Sattriya dance]] ([[Assam]])</center>\nFile:Bihu dance of Assam.jpg|[[Assamese people|Assamese]] youths performing [[Bihu dance]].\nFile:Nyokum festival Nyishi.JPG|<center>Nyokum festival of [[Nyishi (Tribe)|Nyishi tribe]] ([[Arunachal Pradesh]])</center>\nFile:Jagoi Manipuri dance 2.jpg|<center>[[Manipuri dance]]</center>\nFile:Bodo dance.jpg|<center>[[Bagurumba]] dance of [[Bodo people|Bodo tribe]] ([[Assam]])</center>\nFile:Wangala Dance.1.JPG|<center>[[Wangala]] dance of [[Garo people|Garo tribe]] ([[Assam]], [[Meghalaya]])</center>\nFile:Angami 1863b.jpg|<center>Dance of [[Angami Naga|Angami tribe]] ([[Nagaland]])</center>\nFile:Traditional dance.jpg|<center>Students performing traditional dance at [[Jorethang]] ([[Sikkim]])</center> \n</gallery>\n\n===Music===\nNortheast is a hub of different genres of music. Each community has its own rich heritage of folk music. Talented musicians and singers are plentifully found in this part of the country. The Assamese singer-composer [[Bhupen Hazarika]] achieved national and international fame with his remarkable creations. Another famous singer from Assam, [[Pratima Barua Pandey]] is a well-known folk singer. [[Zubeen Garg]], [[Papon (Assamese singer)|Papon]], [[Anurag Saikia]] are some other notable singers, musicians from the state of [[Assam]]. [[Tangkhul Naga]] folk blue singer like [[Rewben Mashangva]], who comes from Ukhrul, is an acclaimed Folk singer whose music is inspired by the like of Bob Dylan and Bob Marley. Another famous folk singing band from Nagaland popularly known as [[Tetseo Sisters]] is one to be noted for their original music genre. However, younger generation has started pursuing western music more and more nowadays. Northeast is witnessing immense rise of musical revolution in the 21st century. {{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n===Literature===\nMany of the Northeast Indian indigenous communities have an ancient heritage of [[Folklore genre|folktales]] which tell the tale of their origin, rituals, beliefs and so on. These tales are transmitted from one generation to another in oral form. They are remarkable instances of tribal wisdom and imagination. However, Assam and Manipur have some ancient written texts. These states were mentioned in the great Hindu epic [[Mahabharata]]. The [[Saptakanda Ramayana]] in [[Assamese language|Assamese]] by [[Madhava Kandali]] is considered the first translation of the Sanskrit [[Ramayana]] into a modern [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan Language]]. ''Karbi Ramayana'' bears witness to the old heritage of written literature in Assam. Two writers from the Northeast, viz., [[Birendra Kumar Bhattacharya]] and [[Mamoni Raisom Goswami]], have been awarded [[Jnanpith Award|Jnanpith]], the highest literary award in India.<ref name=\"Jnanpith {{!}} Laureates\">{{Cite web|url=http://jnanpith.net/laureates.html?id=3#list-3|title=Jnanpith {{!}} Laureates|website=jnanpith.net|access-date=2019-07-23}}</ref> Hence, [[Birendra Kumar Bhattacharya]] was the first [[Assamese language|Assamese]] writer and from the Northeast India to receive [[Jnanpith Award]] for his [[Assamese language|Assamese]] novel ''Mrityunjay(1979).''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/assamese-manipuri-naga-authors-have-kept-alive-world-war-ii-fought-70-years-ago/|title=Assamese, Manipuri, Naga authors have kept alive World War II fought 70 years ago|date=2015-05-08|website=The Indian Express|language=en-IN|access-date=2019-07-23}}</ref> [[Mamoni Raisom Goswami]] was awarded the [[Jnanpith Award]] in the year 2000.<ref name=\"Jnanpith {{!}} Laureates\"/> [[Nagen Saikia]] is the first writer from [[Assam]] and the Northeast India, to have been conferred the prestigious [[Sahitya Akademi Fellowship]] by the [[Sahitya Akademi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sahitya-akademi.gov.in/fellows/sahitya_akademi_fellowship.jsp#Sahitya%20Akademi%20Fellows|title=..:: SAHITYA : Fellows and Honorary Fellows ::..|website=sahitya-akademi.gov.in|access-date=2019-07-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sahitya-akademi.gov.in/pdf/fellows_29-1-2019.pdf|title=Press release, election of fellows of Sahitya Akademy.|date=January 29, 2019|website=Sahitya Akademi|archive-url=http://sahitya-akademi.gov.in|archive-date=January 29, 2019|url-status=|access-date=2019-07-23}}</ref> The last quarter of the 20th century saw the rise of modern literature in the Northeast. Most of the writers, especially the tribal writers, are bilingual, that is, they write both in their mother-tongue and English. Some of the general features of this literature are\u2014retrieval of folklore, celebration of folk culture, identity politics, reaction to the insurgency and counter-insurgency operations, depiction of natural beauty, changes meted out by time, etc. The major writers of Northeast Literature are--(from Assam) [[Lakshminath Bezbaroa]], [[Homen Borgohain]], [[Birendra Kumar Bhattacharya]], [[Harekrishna Deka]], [[Rongbong Terang]], [[Nilmani Phukan]], [[Indira Goswami]], [[Hiren Bhattacharyya]], [[Mitra Phukan]], [[Jahnavi Barua]], [[Dhruba Hazarika]], [[Rita Chowdhury]], D N Bezbarua, Nilim Kumar, Anupama Basumatary, Uddipana Goswami, Anjum Hassan, Aruni Kashyap; (from Arunachal Pradesh) [[Mamang Dai]]; (from Manipur) [[Robin S Ngangom]], [[Ratan Thiyam]], Thangjam Ibopishak, Gambhini Devi, T Bijoykumar Singh; (from Meghalaya) Kynpham Sing Nongkynrih, Esther Syiem, Desmond Kharmawphlang, Paul Lyngdoh; (from Mizoram) Mona Zote; (from Nagaland) [[Temsula Ao]], Cherrie Chhangte, [[Easterine Kire]]; (from Sikkim) Sudha M Rai, Rajendra Bhandari (from Tripura) Chandrakanta Murasingh. Temsula Ao is the first writer from Northeast India to be awarded the [[Sahitya Akademi Award]] (2013) in the Indian English Literature category for her collection of short stories, ''Laburnum for My Head'', and [[Padma Shri|Padmashree]] (2007). Easterine Kire is the first English novelist hailed from Nagaland. She received [[The Hindu Literary Prize]] (2015) for her novel ''When the River Sleeps''. Indira Goswami, alias Mamoni Roisom Goswami, is an acclaimed Assamese writer whose novels include ''Moth-Eaten Howda of the Tusker'', ''Pages Stained with Blood'', ''The Shadow of Kamakhya'' and ''The Blue-Necked God''. Mamang Dai won the [[Sahitya Akademi Award]] (2017) for her novel ''The Black Hill''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sahitya-akademi.gov.in/awards/akademi%20samman_suchi.jsp|title=..:: SAHITYA : Akademi Awards ::..|website=sahitya-akademi.gov.in|access-date=2019-07-23}}</ref>\n\n==Administration and political disputes==\n===International borders management===\n* [[McMahon Line]] and [[:Category:China\u2013India border crossings|China\u2013India border crossings]] manned by [[Indo-Tibetan Border Police]] and [[Special Frontier Force]] with China along Sikkim and Arunachal Pradesh\n* [[Bangladesh\u2013India border|India-Bangladesh border]] and [[Transport between India and Bangladesh|crossings]] manned by [[Border Security Force]] along Assam, Meghalaya, Tripura and Mizoram \n* [[India\u2013Myanmar barrier]], [[India\u2013Myanmar barrier#International border crossings|crossings]]  manned by [[Assam Rifles]] and [[Indian Army]] along Arunachal Pradesh, Nagaland, Manipur and Mizoram\n* [[Bhutan\u2013India border|India-Bhutan borders]] manned by [[Sashastra Seema Bal]] along Sikkim, Assam and Arunachal Pradesh\n* [[India\u2013Nepal relations|India-Nepal border]] manned by Sashastra Seema Bal along Sikkim\n\n===Pan-states development authorities===\n* [[Ministry for Development of North Eastern Region]] (DoNER)\n* [[North Eastern Council]]\n\n===States and sub-divisions===\n{{main|Administrative divisions of India|List of districts in India}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"background:#fff;font-size:0.9em;\"\n|-\n! State!! [[ISO 3166-2:IN|Code]