agaland records negative decadal growth\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/Nagaland-records-negative-growth-in-decadal-population/article14666718.ece |title=Nagaland records negative decadal growth}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:0.9em;background:#ffffff;width:100%;text-align:right;\"\n|-\n! State\n! Population\n! Males !! Females\n! Sex Ratio\n! Literacy %\n! Rural Population\n! Urban Population\n! Area (km\u00b2)\n! Density (/km\u00b2)\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Arunachal Pradesh ||  1,383,727 || 713,912 || 669,815 || 938 || 65.38 || 870,087\n| 227,881 || 83,743 || 17\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Assam || 31,205,576 || 15,939,443 || 15,266,133 || 958 || 72.19 || 23,216,288\n| 3,439,240 || 78,438 || 397\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Manipur || 2,570,390 || 1,290,171 || 1,280,219 || 992 || 79.21 || 1,590,820 || 575,968\n| 22,327 || 122\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Meghalaya || 2,966,889 || 1,491,832 || 1,475,057 || 989 || 74.43 || 1,864,711 || 454,111\n| 22,429 || 132\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Mizoram || 1,097,206 || 555,339 || 541,867 || 976 || 91.33 || 447,567 || 441,006\n| 21,081 || 52\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Nagaland || 1,978,502 || 1,024,649 || 953,853 || 931 || 79.55 || 1,647,249 || 342,787\n| 16,579 || 119\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Sikkim || 610,577 || 323,070 || 287,507 || 890 || 81.42 || 480,981 || 59,870 || 7,096\n| 86\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;text-align:left;\"|Tripura || 3,673,917 || 1,874,376 || 1,799,541 || 960 || 87.22 || 2,653,453 || 545,750\n| 10,486 || 350\n|}\n\n===Largest cities by population===\n{{main|List of cities in India by population|List of cities in Assam by population}}\nAccording to [[2011 Census of India]], the largest cities in Northeast India are \n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:0.9em;background:#ffffff;text-align:center;min-width:70%;\"\n! Rank !! City !! Type !!State !!Population !!Rank !! City !! Type !!State !!Population\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|1 || [[Guwahati]] ||align=\"center\"|UA||Assam || align=\"right\" | 968,549||style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|9 || [[Jorhat]]  ||UA ||Assam|| align=\"right\" | 153,889\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|2 || [[Agartala]]  ||style=\"background:#fEE0F2;\"|City||Tripura || align=\"right\" | 522,613|| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|10 || [[Nagaon]]  ||UA ||Assam|| align=\"right\" | 147,496\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|3 || [[Imphal]]  ||align=\"center\"|UA ||Manipur|| align=\"right\" |  414,288||style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|11 || [[Tinsukia]]  ||UA ||Assam|| align=\"right\" | 126,389\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|4 || [[Dimapur]]   ||style=\"background:#fEE0F2;\"|City||Nagaland|| align=\"right\" | 379,769|| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|12 || [[Dhubri]]  ||UA ||Assam|| align=\"right\" | 109,234\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|5 || [[Shillong]]  ||UA ||Meghalaya|| align=\"right\" | 354,325|| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|13 || [[Tezpur]]  ||UA ||Assam|| align=\"right\" | 102,505\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|6 || [[Aizawl]]   ||style=\"background:#fEE0F2;\"|City ||Mizoram|| align=\"right\" |  291,822|| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|14 || [[Kohima]]  ||UA ||Nagaland|| align=\"right\" | 100,000\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|7 || [[Silchar]]   ||UA ||Assam|| align=\"right\" | 229,136|| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|15 || [[Gangtok]]  ||style=\"background:#fEE0F2;\"|City ||Sikkim || align=\"right\" | 98,658\n|- \n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|8 || [[Dibrugarh]]  ||UA  ||Assam|| align=\"right\" | 154,296|| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|16 || [[Itanagar]]  ||style=\"background:#fEE0F2;\"|City ||Arunachal Pradesh|| align=\"right\" | 95,650\n|-\n| colspan=\"10\" align=\"left\"|\n''UA'': Urban Agglomeration<ref>http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_3_PR_UA_Citiees_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf</ref>\n|- \n|}\n\n===Languages===\nNortheast India constitutes a single linguistic region within the Indian national context, with about 220 languages in multiple language families ([[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]], [[Sino-Tibetan languages|Sino-Tibetan]], [[Kra\u2013Dai languages|Kra\u2013Dai]], [[Austroasiatic languages|Austroasiatic]], as well as some creole languages) that share a number of features that set them apart from most other areas of the Indian subcontinent (such as alveolar consonants rather than the more typical dental/retroflex distinction).<ref name=\"moral97_42\">{{harv|Moral|1997|p=42}}</ref><ref name=\"IITG-languages_of_ne\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.iitg.ernet.in/rcilts/phaseI/heirarchy.htm |title=IITG - Hierarchy of North Eastern Languages}}</ref> [[Assamese language|Assamese]], an [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan language]] spoken mostly in the [[Brahmaputra Valley]], developed as a ''lingua franca'' for many speech communities.  Assamese-based pidgin/creoles have developed in Nagaland ([[Nagamese]]) and Arunachal ([[Nefamese]]),<ref>{{harv|Moral|1997|pp=43\u201344}}</ref> though their use has been on a decline in recent times.  The Austro-Asiatic family is represented by the [[Khasi language|Khasi]], [[Jaintia language|Jaintia]] and [[War language|War]] languages of Meghalaya. A small number of Tai\u2013Kadai languages (Ahom, Tai Phake, Khamti, etc.) are also spoken. Sino-Tibetan is represented by a number of languages that differ significantly from each other,<ref name=BlenchPost13>Blench, R. & Post, M. W. (2013). [https://www.academia.edu/627686/Rethinking_Sino-Tibetan_phylogeny_from_the_perspective_of_North_East_Indian_languages Rethinking Sino-Tibetan phylogeny from the perspective of Northeast Indian languages]</ref> some of which are: [[Bodo language|Bodo]], Rabha, Karbi, Mising, Tiwa, [[Deori language|Deori]], Biate etc. (Assam); Garo, Hajong, Biate (Meghalaya) Ao, Angami, Sema, Lotha, Konyak etc.(Nagaland); Mizo, [[Hmar language|Hmar]], [[Chakma language|Chakma]] etc. (Mizoram); Hrusso, Tanee, Nisi, Adi, Abor, Nocte, Apatani, Misimi etc. (Arunachal). [[Meitei language|Meitei]] is the official language in Manipur, the dominant language of the Imphal Valley; while \"Naga\" languages such as [[Poula language|Poumai]], [[Sopvoma language|Mao]], Maram, Rongmei (Kabui) and Tangkul, and Kuki-Chin languages such as Thadou-Kuki, Mizo, [[Hmar language|Hmar]], Simte and Paite predominate in individual hill areas of the state.<ref name=PostBurling17>Post, M. W. and R. Burling (2017). [https://www.academia.edu/17070971/The_Tibeto-Burman_languages_of_Northeast_India The Tibeto-Burman languages of Northeast India]</ref>\n\nAmong other Indo-Aryan languages, [[Bengali language|Bengali]] is spoken in South Assam in the Barak Valley. Besides the Sino-Tibetan [[Kokborok|Tripuri language]], [[Bengali language|Bengali]] is a majority language in Tripura. [[Nepali language|Nepali]], an Indo-Aryan language, is dominant in [[Sikkim]], besides the Sino-Tibetan languages [[Limbu language|Limbu]], [[Bhutia language|Bhutia]] and [[Lepcha language|Lepcha]]. Bengali was the official language of [[Colonial Assam]] for about forty years from the 1830s.\n\n====Official languages====\n{{See also|Languages with official status in India}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:0.9em;min-width:70%;background:#ffffff;\"\n|-\n! State\n! Official Languages<ref name=\"NER official languages\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.mcrg.ac.in/Core/Northeast_Report.pdf |title=Report On North East India}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Arunachal Pradesh || [[Hindi language|Hindi]], [[English language|English]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Assam || [[Assamese language|Assamese]], [[Bengali language|Bengali]] (in the [[Barak Valley]]), [[Bodo language|Bodo]] (in [[Bodoland]])\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Manipur || [[Meitei language|Meiteilon]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Meghalaya || [[Khasi language|Khasi]], [[Garo language|Garo]], [[English language|English]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Mizoram || [[Mizo language|Mizo]], [[English language|English]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Nagaland || [[English language|English]]<ref name=\"Nagaland State Profile\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nagaland.gov.in/portal/portal/StatePortal/AboutNagaland/StateProfile |title=Nagaland State Profile}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Sikkim || [[Nepali language|Nepali]], [[English language|English]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Tripura || [[Bengali language|Bengali]], [[Kokborok]], [[English language|English]]<ref>https://tripura.gov.in/know-tripura</ref>\n|}\n\n====Etymology of state names====\n{{See also|Nomenclature of States in North East India|List of Indian state and union territory name etymologies}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:0.9em;min-width:70%;background:#ffffff;\"\n|-\n! Name of state\n! Origin\n! Literal meaning\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Arunachal Pradesh || [[Sanskrit]] || ''Land of the rising sun''\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|[[Etymology of Assam|Assam]] ||  Native word || Name derived from the ''[[Ahom people]](?)''<ref>\"Ahoms also gave Assam and its language their name ('\n|'Ahom'' and the modern ''\u0252\u03c7\u0252m'' 'Assam' come from an attested earlier form ''asam'', ''acam'', probably from a Burmese corruption of the word ''Shan/Shyam'', cf. ''Siam'': Kakati 1962; 1-4).\" {{harv|Masica|1993|p=50}}</ref>, and also from the Sanskrit word ''asama'', meaning \"uneven\"(?)<ref>\"According to some, the word is derived from ''Asama''meaning \"uneven\", as distinguished from Samatata, or the level plains of East Bengal.\" {{harv|Gait|1906|p=241}}</ref> \n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|[[wiktionary:Manipur|Manipur]] || [[Sanskrit]] || ''Land abundant with jewels'', adopted in the 18th century\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Meghalaya || [[Sanskrit]] || ''Abode of the clouds'', coined by [[Shiba P. Chatterjee]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Mizoram || [[Mizo language]] ||  ''Land of the Hilly people''; ''Ram'' - means land \n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Nagaland || [[English language|English]] || ''Land of the Naga people''\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|Sikkim || [[Limbu language|Limbu Language]] || ''New House'' \u2013 Derived from the word ''\"Sukhim\"'', \"Su\" meaning new and \"Khim\" meaning house\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f7f7fe;\"|[[Tripura#Etymology|Tripura]] || [[Kokborok]] || [[Sanskrit]] version of native names: Tipra, Tuipura, [[Twipra Kingdom|Twipra]] etc. It literally means ''Land near the Water'' \u2013 Derived from the word ''\"TWIPRA\"'', \"Twi\" meaning water and \"Bupra\" meaning near. As [[Tripura]] is slightly near the [[Bay of Bengal]]\n|}\n\n====Endangered languages====\n{{Main|List of endangered languages in India}}\nGiven the diverse population in the region with only a few widely spoken ones recognised as the [[official language]]s by both the [[State government|state]] and [[Central government|central]] governments, a large number of languages from the North Eastern Region of [[India]] have become vulnerable. Without proper teaching and preservation efforts, the already underdeveloped [[literature]] of the endangered languages are on the verge of extinction. Additionally, the younger generation are rapidly adopting the widely spoken languages to secure employment and livelihood.<ref name=\"Endangered languages of North-east India\">{{Cite web |url=https://smritikumarsinha.wordpress.com/northeast-a-war-and-peace-painting/ |title=Endangered languages of North-east India}}</ref>\n\n===Religions===\n\n{{Pie chart |thumb = right\n|caption = Religion in Northeast India (2011)\n|label1 = [[Hinduism]]|color1 = Orange\n|value1 = 58.06\n|label2 = [[Islam]]|color2 = Green \n|value2 = 23\n|label3 = [[Christianity]]|color3 = DodgerBlue\n|value3 = 16.89\